				\begin{document}$$p(y=1)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M222"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq132.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, we can quantify the power of these two surrogate approaches. As a result we can use the <inline-formula id="IEq133"><alternatives><tex-math id="M223">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$G(X;{\widetilde{Y}_0})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M224"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x0037e;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq133.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and/or <inline-formula id="IEq134"><alternatives><tex-math id="M225">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
