				\begin{document}$$G(X;\widetilde{Y}_1)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M226"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x0037e;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq134.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> instead of the <italic>G</italic>(<italic>X</italic>;&#x000a0;<italic>Y</italic>) for power analysis and sample size determination. Taking advantage of the extra degree of freedom in <inline-formula id="IEq135"><alternatives><tex-math id="M227">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
