				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p({\widetilde{y}_0=1})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M228"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq135.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and/or <inline-formula id="IEq136"><alternatives><tex-math id="M229">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p(\widetilde{y}_1=0)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M230"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq136.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, we can also determine the <italic>required level of supervision</italic> (i.e. number of labelled examples) needed, following the same procedure as in sample size determination. In our previous work (Sechidis et&#x000a0;al. <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR41">2014</xref>), we presented a complete methodology for sample/labelled size determination in positive-unlabelled scenarios by using the <inline-formula id="IEq137"><alternatives><tex-math id="M231">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\kappa _{{\widetilde{Y}_0}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M232"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003ba;</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq137.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> correction factor and surrogate <inline-formula id="IEq138"><alternatives><tex-math id="M233">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\widetilde{Y}_0}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M234"><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq138.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p><p>Interestingly, to decide which of these two tests is more powerful we do not need exact prior knowledge, but we can do so by using some <italic>&#x0201c;soft&#x0201d; prior knowledge</italic> expressed in terms of inequality. Before presenting this result, let us define first the following threshold:</p></sec><sec id="FPar12"><title>Definition 3</title><p id="Par75">(<italic>Switching threshold</italic>) The switching threshold value (<inline-formula id="IEq139"><alternatives><tex-math id="M235">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi $$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M236"><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003d5;</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq139.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>) is<disp-formula id="Equ20"><alternatives><tex-math id="M237">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \phi = \frac{1}{1+\sqrt{\frac{(1-p({\widetilde{y}_0=1}))p(\widetilde{y}_1=0)}{p({\widetilde{y}_0=1})(1-p(\widetilde{y}_1=0))}}}. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M238" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003d5;</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:msqrt><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:msqrt></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_Equ20.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>
</p><p>This threshold can be estimated using the values of the observed variables <inline-formula id="IEq140"><alternatives><tex-math id="M239">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
