				\begin{document}$$J^Y$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M380"><mml:msup><mml:mi>J</mml:mi><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi></mml:msup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq229.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> which uses the mutual information between the features and the unobservable variable <italic>Y</italic>, and <inline-formula id="IEq230"><alternatives><tex-math id="M381">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$J^{\widetilde{Y}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M382"><mml:msup><mml:mi>J</mml:mi><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:msup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq230.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> which uses the mutual information between the features and the surrogate <inline-formula id="IEq231"><alternatives><tex-math id="M383">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
