				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\rho $$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M440"><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003c1;</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq257.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> (average over 10 repetitions) between population ranking and ranking derived through different surrogate approaches. For each repetition we average over 30 semi-supervised versions with <inline-formula id="IEq258"><alternatives><tex-math id="M441">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p(s=1) = 0.25$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M442"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>s</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq258.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and sampled by: <bold>a</bold> MCAR and <bold>b</bold> MAR-C with <inline-formula id="IEq259"><alternatives><tex-math id="M443">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p(y=1|s=1) = 0.50$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M444"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">|</mml:mo><mml:mi>s</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.50</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq259.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. To help the visibility, we plot only the most powerful option between surrogates 2 and 3, which in both scenarios is surrogate 2. <bold>a</bold> MCAR. <bold>b</bold> MAR-C</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Fig5_HTML" id="MO21"/></fig>
</p></sec></sec><sec id="Sec19"><title>Ranking: labels are missing at random class dependent (MAR-C)</title><p id="Par105">In this scenario it is impossible to derive relationships for <bold>Surrogate&#x000a0;1</bold> (i.e. ignore the unlabelled examples), but only for the following two surrogate approaches (see proof of Theorem <xref ref-type="sec" rid="FPar10">4</xref>):<disp-formula id="Equ23"><alternatives><tex-math id="M445">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned}&#x00026;\mathbf{Surrogate~2}~({\widetilde{Y}_0}):~I_2(X;{\widetilde{Y}_0}) = \frac{1-p(y=1)}{p(y=1)} \frac{p({\widetilde{y}_0=1})}{1-p({\widetilde{y}_0=1})}I_2(X;Y),&#x00026;\\&#x00026;\mathbf{Surrogate~3}~(\widetilde{Y}_1):~I_2(X;\widetilde{Y}_1) = \frac{1-p(y=0)}{p(y=0)} \frac{p(\widetilde{y}_1=0)}{1-p(\widetilde{y}_1=0)}I_2(X;Y).&#x00026;\end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M446" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd/><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">Surrogate</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="3.33333pt"/><mml:mn mathvariant="bold">2</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="3.33333pt"/><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:mspace width="3.33333pt"/><mml:msub><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x0037e;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:msub><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x0037e;</mml:mo><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>,</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd><mml:mtd/></mml:mtr><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mrow/></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">Surrogate</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="3.33333pt"/><mml:mn mathvariant="bold">3</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="3.33333pt"/><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:mspace width="3.33333pt"/><mml:msub><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x0037e;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:msub><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x0037e;</mml:mo><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_Equ23.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>Again, we observe that all of the mutual information quantities of the <italic>LHS</italic> can be written as <inline-formula id="IEq260"><alternatives><tex-math id="M447">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\kappa $$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M448"><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003ba;</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq260.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> times the mutual information derived by using the unobservable variable <italic>Y</italic>,&#x000a0; where the factor <inline-formula id="IEq261"><alternatives><tex-math id="M449">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\kappa $$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M450"><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003ba;</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq261.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is independent of the characteristics of the feature <italic>X</italic>. A consequence of these relationships is that the mutual information quantities of the <italic>LHS</italic> can be used to rank the features, and the ranking will be the same as if we had used the unobservable variable <italic>Y</italic>.</p><p id="Par106">Another interesting consequence is that we can rank the features <italic>without</italic> an exact prior knowledge over the <inline-formula id="IEq262"><alternatives><tex-math id="M451">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p(y=1)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M452"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq262.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> by simply using Surrogate 2 or 3. Deciding the optimal choice between these two surrogates has to do with the accuracy of the estimators, which can be answered by using our findings in hypothesis testing (Sect.&#x000a0;<xref rid="Sec13" ref-type="sec">3.3</xref>), since the most powerful test leads to more accurate estimators (Loftus <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR30">1991</xref>). Thus we can suggest the following theorem.</p><sec id="FPar21"><title>Theorem 8</title><p id="Par107">(MAR-C: Ranking by using &#x0201c;soft&#x0201d; prior knowledge) In MAR-C the rankings derived by <bold>Surrogate 2</bold> or <bold>Surrogate 3</bold> are ranking equivalent to the population ranking: <inline-formula id="IEq263"><alternatives><tex-math id="M453">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$J_{MIM}^Y \mathop = \limits ^R J_{MIM}^{{\widetilde{Y}_0}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M454"><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>J</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:mover><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>R</mml:mi></mml:mover><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>J</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:msubsup></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq263.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula id="IEq264"><alternatives><tex-math id="M455">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$J_{MIM}^Y \mathop = \limits ^R J_{MIM}^{\widetilde{Y}_1}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M456"><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>J</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:mover><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>R</mml:mi></mml:mover><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>J</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:msubsup></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq264.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Furthermore, when <inline-formula id="IEq265"><alternatives><tex-math id="M457">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p(y=1) &#x0003c; \phi $$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M458"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>&#x0003c;</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003d5;</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq265.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> holds the the optimal choice is <bold>Surrogate 2</bold> (<inline-formula id="IEq266"><alternatives><tex-math id="M459">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\widetilde{Y}_0}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M460"><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq266.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>) while when the opposing inequality holds, the most optimal choice is <bold>Surrogate 3</bold> (<inline-formula id="IEq267"><alternatives><tex-math id="M461">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\widetilde{Y}_1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M462"><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq267.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>). When equality holds, both approaches are equivalent.</p><p>Proving this theorem is straightforward, by using Theorem <xref ref-type="sec" rid="FPar13">5</xref> and the fact that the most powerful way for testing will result in the most accurate estimator (Loftus <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR30">1991</xref>), and as a result a ranking that is closer to the ideal unobservable ranking. Figure&#x000a0;<xref rid="Fig5" ref-type="fig">5</xref>b verifies the results of this section. To generate the semi-supervised data again we used the same methodology as in Sect.&#x000a0;<xref rid="Sec13" ref-type="sec">3.3</xref>. When we have &#x0201c;soft&#x0201d; prior knowledge we can decide the optimal choice between <inline-formula id="IEq268"><alternatives><tex-math id="M463">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hat{I}(X;{\widetilde{Y}_0})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M464"><mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x0037e;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq268.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula id="IEq269"><alternatives><tex-math id="M465">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hat{I}(X;\widetilde{Y}_1)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M466"><mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x0037e;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq269.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. In this setting, since <inline-formula id="IEq270"><alternatives><tex-math id="M467">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p({\widetilde{y}_0=1})=p(\widetilde{y}_1=0)=0.125$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M468"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.125</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq270.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, the <italic>RHS</italic> of the inequality (<xref rid="Equ4" ref-type="">4</xref>) becomes 0.50, which is larger than 0.20 and as result the ranking derived through <inline-formula id="IEq271"><alternatives><tex-math id="M469">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hat{I}(X;{\widetilde{Y}_0})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M470"><mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>I</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x0037e;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq271.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> will be closer to the population ranking than the one derived by <inline-formula id="IEq272"><alternatives><tex-math id="M471">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
