				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\alpha =0.05$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M700"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003b1;</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.05</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq408.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>), the desired probability of type II error (e.g. <inline-formula id="IEq409"><alternatives><tex-math id="M701">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta = 0.01$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M702"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003b2;</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.01</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq409.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> or <inline-formula id="IEq410"><alternatives><tex-math id="M703">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$power = 0.99$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M704"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mi>o</mml:mi><mml:mi>w</mml:mi><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.99</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq410.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>) and the desired effect size that we want to observe (i.e. expressed in terms of <italic>I</italic>(<italic>X</italic>;&#x000a0;<italic>Y</italic>) for the <italic>G</italic>-test), and we can determine the minimum number of examples (<italic>N</italic>) that we need to detect that effect. However, to do this we need a test statistic with a known distribution under the alternative hypothesis. It is known that the <italic>G</italic>-statistic has a large-sample <italic>non-central</italic>
<inline-formula id="IEq411"><alternatives><tex-math id="M705">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
