				\begin{document}$$\mathbf{Surrogate~3}~(\widetilde{Y}_1)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M726"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">Surrogate</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="3.33333pt"/><mml:mn mathvariant="bold">3</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="3.33333pt"/><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq422.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>: We can prove that these surrogate approaches are valid by following the same methodology, or we can read that the independence relationships hold from the <italic>m</italic>-graph of MCAR in Fig.&#x000a0;<xref rid="Fig2" ref-type="fig">2</xref>a. <inline-formula id="IEq423"><alternatives><tex-math id="M727">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
