<inline-formula id="IEq432"><alternatives><tex-math id="M747">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf{Surrogate~2}~({\widetilde{Y}_0})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M748"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">Surrogate</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="3.33333pt"/><mml:mn mathvariant="bold">2</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="3.33333pt"/><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq432.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>: In order to prove that relationship we will use the result of Shelby (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR45">1974</xref>) that when we assume local alternatives the <inline-formula id="IEq433"><alternatives><tex-math id="M749">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
