				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$X^2$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M750"><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq433.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and the <italic>G</italic>-test have the same asymptotic power (Shelby <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR45">1974</xref>,&#x000a0;p. 109), in other words their non-centrality parameters converge to a common value as <inline-formula id="IEq434"><alternatives><tex-math id="M751">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$N \rightarrow \infty $$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M752"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">&#x02192;</mml:mo><mml:mi>&#x0221e;</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="10994_2017_5648_Article_IEq434.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> (Agresti <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR1">2013</xref>,&#x000a0;Section 16.3.5). So instead of exploring the relationship of the non-centrality parameters for the <italic>G</italic>-tests between <inline-formula id="IEq435"><alternatives><tex-math id="M753">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
